title: For Sale:   M1854 VOLCANIC NAVY 36 CALIBER ROCKET BALL PISTOL
postcontent: S172K, Invented in 1854 and produced in several calibers. This specimen is bored and chambered in 36 caliber. Since no one has ever located one, it was presumed that they were never made in this caliber. The Volcanic Pistol/Rifle however, is often found in 36 caliber, which has kept alive the controversy over the question; why did they make a rifle and a rifle/pistol with detachable shoulder stock in the 36 caliber, and not bother to use the same tooling to make the Navy pistol in 36 caliber (since they bothered to make them in all the other calibers). The answer to that has only recently been revealed with the discovery of this 36 caliber specimen. At first mistaken to be a replica, the previous owners/sellers have volunteered the latest information. This gun was originally found as parts, in a bin where more of the same were stored, in varying states of rough castings, unfinished and finished parts and assemblies, in the 1950's. These surplus parts lots were cobbled together into about 20 finished pieces and sold to collectors. Among them were a few 36 caliber specimens. An affidavit with all the details accompanies this auction piece and it includes the involvement of the most famous antique gun dealer in history, BANNERMAN's. On the top flat of the 8" octagon barrel assembly, it is clearly marked, "THE VOLCANIC REPEATING ARMS CO PATENT NEW HAVEN CONN FEB. 14, 1854." Overall length is 15". Fine walnut grips, fully functional, bored and chambered for the 36 caliber rocket ball ammunition. The main spring seems weak, unfired condition throughout. It's not just an antique gun for sale here, it's a missing link which, with this affidavit, answers the question of why no Volcanic Navy pistols in 36 caliber have been found...until now. Own a legend and make history with it. Sold as-is, with affidavit. All original and complete, ship weight is 5 pounds. 60 day layaway is available. Credit cards welcome plus 4% and must be pre-approved in advance, due to the size of the potential charge. SAFETY NOTICE: We do not sell firearms, only collectible antiques, if you shoot them, it's at your own risk and we are not liable for anything you do.

title: For Sale:  1873 U.S 6th Calvery Colt 45 Serial# 2004 WITH COA!
postcontent:
Gun is housed in special collections divisions in Tulsa and can be viewed by appointment only. Please email for an appointment.
One of the earliest cartridge Colts known to exist and now on the market...having Serial number #2004. U.S. Marked. Comes from Lot 2 issued in 1873  This is an EXCEDDINGLY RARE piece of history, Issued to 6th cavalry to fight the Native Americans "Possibly Little Big Horn" Custer colt. This gun locks up and indexes perfect and has been tested with blanks. The fact that the barrell was cut to non-standard length is strong evidence it was taken by the Native Americans during a battle and modified as this was the common practice. As well as the holster having a strong Native influence hand made as well as the knife. The handle was checkered likely by a simple knife probably sitting around a camp fire back in the day. Having the badge from 6th cavalary also suggest it was taken by Natives after a kill as this was common to use for trade goods as well as a battle keep-sake to show bravery within the tribe. This gun was used!!! And if it could talk. 
The gun was taken to an expert smith and the screws were replaced during the cleaning and initial repair, but the original screws are now back in the gun. The gun was plum colored from age and after inspection and cleaning was put back to plum to preserve the original color..
The John Kopec letter states the history of this gun with much detail and John Kopec is the worlds leading colt expert having devoted his life to the study of this period colt revolver. 
Comes with period holster and knife and 1876 6th Cavalry badge and 6 period ammo rounds "One round has an X carved on it" Also comes with COA. Please feel free to ask any questions. This is a museum piece for the serious collector.  Once again, this gun is housed in a special collections division and can be viewed by appointment only.
